{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592184"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:13:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:13:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15228"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15228"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.53,0.23,0.03,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65132"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7919"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15228"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50568"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1017"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8572"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19296"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21638"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65132"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EColorectal cancer treatment options vary based on disease stage, location, and genetic predisposition. Surgical treatments can varying from local resection, through segmental resection to total proctocolectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would most likely require a total colectomy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the rectum","Hereditary Non-Polyposis Colorectal Cancer","Liver metastases from colorectal cancer","Localised sigmoid adenocarcinoma","Submucosal invasion in the ascending colon"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe surgical approach to colorectal cancer depends on multiple factors including the stage of disease and genetic risk profile. \u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary Non-Polyposis Colorectal Cancer\u003C/strong\u003E (Lynch syndrome) carries a high risk of developing synchronous and metachronous colorectal cancers, necessitating prophylactic total colectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor \u003Cstrong\u003Elocalised sigmoid adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, a segmental resection (sigmoid colectomy) is typically sufficient. \u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the rectum\u003C/strong\u003E may be managed with local excision for in situ disease or more formal segmental resection, depending on the staging of the disease. \u003Cstrong\u003ESubmucosal invasion in the ascending colon\u003C/strong\u003E typically requires a right hemicolectomy rather than total colectomy. In cases of \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver metastases\u003C/strong\u003E, the surgical approach to the primary tumour would still typically involve segmental resection rather than total colectomy, with separate consideration for management of metastases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hereditary Non-Polyposis Colorectal Cancer (Lynch syndrome) requires prophylactic total colectomy due to high risk of synchronous and metachronous tumours.","Total colectomy is not the standard treatment for localised colorectal cancer where segmental resection is preferred.","Surgical approach in colorectal cancer is guided by cancer stage and genetic risk factors."],"references":["Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Sandler RS. Epidemiology and risk factors for colorectal cancer. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 1996 Dec;25(4):717-35. doi: 10.1016/s0889-8553(05)70271-5. PMID: 8960889","Rawla P, Sunkara T, Barsouk A. Epidemiology of colorectal cancer: incidence, mortality, survival, and risk factors. Prz Gastroenterol. 2019;14(2):89-103. doi: 10.5114/pg.2018.81072. Epub 2019 Jan 6. PMID: 31616522; PMCID: PMC6791134","Kumar A, Gautam V, Sandhu A, Rawat K, Sharma A, Saha L. Current and emerging therapeutic approaches for colorectal cancer: A comprehensive review. World J Gastrointest Surg. 2023 Apr 27;15(4):495-519. doi: 10.4240/wjgs.v15.i4.495. PMID: 37206081; PMCID: PMC10190721."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50568"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15228"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50568"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T14:41:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T14:42:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7919"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65132"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.eme